      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nTo simplify our daily lives, we typically assign names to people, animals, objects, and also to numbers (<htcite0>). Sometimes, besides numbers, we use nicknames that can be simplifications of the original name itself. Since we do this throughout our lives, this practice becomes so natural that we often do it without realizing that certain simplifications actually end up completely altering the meaning of something.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "d06e24cb-52e8-4ff8-ae37-12052c91b187",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Numerical Families (Part II)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: It Could Be Like That, But It Isn't</b><br /><br />Can you think of any nickname or simplification that you use and that, in reality, completely changes the understanding of something?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_names",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Naming\n\nSometimes, because something resembles what we know or has similar functions, we are tempted to name it in a way that ends up misrepresenting it. Let's look at some examples.\n\n#### Sacred Mountains\n\nAn already explored example of names applied to constructions that do not possess the name they appear to have are the *Witz*—Maya sacred mountains in America (*Abya Yala*) (**Figure 1**)— which are called “pyramids” (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "5c61211a-87e4-45ee-9d27-739625a7971c",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Together We Are Strong",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"img4\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img4', '0%')\" src=\"images/Xunantunich/WitzXunantunich.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 1</b>: Sacred mountain at Xunantunich, Belize. Photograph taken on <htdate0>, during a visit to the site.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2016",
                     "month": "7",
                     "day": "22"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: What it seems like</b><br /><br />Observe Figure 1 carefully. Does it remind you of a pyramid?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "If your answer was yes, that is not a problem. Your answer indicates that, during your learning process, the concept of a pyramid was possibly not well explained to you. Let's look at the definition of a pyramid to proceed (<htcite0>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "1aae32d7-8b8a-49d9-b136-f859e24a53e6",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "Pirámide",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><ul class=\"citation\"> <li>\"<i>A pyramid is a geometric figure with a closed base and triangular faces that converge at a single point at the top, known as the apex.</i>\"</li></ul></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Now that we have the definition of a pyramid, which reinforces the need for **triangular**, lateral faces, as in **Figure 2**, we can revisit **Reflection 2**.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table class=\"book_navigation\"><tr><td>Pyramid with a Square Base</td><td>Pyramid with a Pentagonal Base</td></tr><tr><td><img id=\"img2\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img2', '0%')\" src=\"images/HistoryTracers/pyramid.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/></td><td><img id=\"img3\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img3', '0%')\" src=\"images/HistoryTracers/pentagonal_pyramid.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/></td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" class=\"desc\"><b>Figure 2</b>: Examples of pyramids illustrating the mathematical definition.</td></tr></table></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 3: Is it really a pyramid?</b><br /><br />Are there triangular faces on the <i>Witz</i> in <b>Figure 1</b>?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Different Letters\n\nIt is not only with geometric figures that mistakes occur. Another example, associated with a cultural issue, would be understanding Chinese characters (**Figure 3**) as if they were Western letters, ignoring the complexity of their structure (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "5c7398a3-7931-4afc-af5e-b505756e8963",
                     "text": "Dai, R., Liu, C. & Xiao, B.",
                     "page": "pp. 2 - 5",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2007",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgChinese\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgChinese', '0%')\" src=\"images/BritishMuseum/mid_RRC5932_14.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 3</b>: Arrowhead made of bone containing an inscription. © Trustees of the British Museum (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillPrimarySource('874a8d48-a892-4ad3-8bc4-b34190bd4eba'); return false;\"><i>The British Museum</i></a> ).</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### What if it was an approximation?\n\nDespite it being tempting to say that, both in the case of the pyramids and the Chinese characters, there was an approximation, in both cases what occurred was a misinterpretation.\n\nBeyond these mistakes, there is another quite common one when we round off or simplify concepts, as we will see next.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_decimal_name",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Names and Abbreviations\n\nIn the same way that we name numbers in units, tens, hundreds, and thousands (<htcite0>), using a family analogy, we also name the numbers we use to count. Furthermore, we use abbreviations for these numbers, as shown in **Table 1**:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "d06e24cb-52e8-4ff8-ae37-12052c91b187",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Numerical Families (Part II)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<style>.localtablename {.width: 60%;margin-left: auto;margin-right: auto;text-align: center;border-collapse: collapse;} .localtablename th {border-collapse: collapse;background-color:lightgrey;} .localtablename td:nth-child(-n+1) {background-color:lightblue;}</style><p><table class=\"localtablename\"><tr><th>Number</th><th>Family</th><th>Prefix</th></tr> <tr><td>1,000,000,000,000,000,000</td><td>Quintillion</td><td>Hexa</td> </tr> <tr><td>1,000,000,000,000,000</td><td>Quadrillion</td><td>Peta</td> </tr>  <tr><td>1,000,000,000,000</td><td>Trillion</td><td>Tera</td> </tr> <tr><td>1,000,000,000</td><td>Billion</td><td>Giga</td> </tr> <tr><td>1,000,000</td><td>Million</td><td>Mega</td> </tr> <tr><td>1,000</td><td>Thousand</td><td>Kilo</td> </tr><tr><td>1</td><td>Units</td><td>&nbsp;</td> </tr> <tr><td>0.1</td><td>Tenths</td><td>Deci</td> </tr> <tr><td>0.01</td><td>Hundredths</td><td>Centi</td> </tr> <tr><td>0.001</td><td>Thousandths</td><td>Mili</td> </tr> <tr><td>0.000001</td><td>Millionth</td><td>Micro</td> </tr> <tr><td>0.000000001</td><td>Billionth</td><td>Nano</td> </tr> <tr><td>0.000000000001</td><td>Trillionth</td><td>Pico</td> </tr> </table></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 1</b>: Names assigned to numbers.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "**Table 1** presents only some of the names we use for numbers; however, numbers are not limited only to the examples shown. This creates an interesting scenario and brings us back again to the question of numerical limits (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "18a901e4-3da3-45d8-a239-fb551e78698e",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Natural Limits",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 4: To infinity…</b><br /><br />If there is no end to decimal numbers, does that mean there are infinite numbers between 0 and 1?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_pi",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### To Be or Not to Be\n\nWhen we buy 1 kilogram of fruit, it is equivalent to saying that we are buying 1000 grams of the same fruit. In this way, the prefix from Table 1 helps us express the quantity of food. It is also not uncommon to hear people who want “1 kilo”, making the prefix represent the 1000 grams we wish to buy.\n\nThese abbreviations made with words might lead us to conclude that we can generalize them to other scenarios, but this can end up leading to errors. For example, in mathematics we define the constant pi (π) as the circumference—the length of a circle if we cut it and stretched it out—**C**, divided by its diameter—the width of the circle, which does not change—**d**, according to **Fórmula 1** (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "a56b7c6c-93ce-4e7f-bf5e-781e4597485d",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"unitaryCircle\" id=\"circtri0\"><style>.circle-draw circle, .circle-draw line {stroke: #71a6d2; stroke-width: 4; stroke-linecap: round; fill: none;} .circle-draw circle { stroke-dasharray: 942; stroke-dashoffset: 942; animation: drawCircle 2s linear forwards;} .radius-line { transform-origin: 300px 150px; animation: rotateRadius 2s linear forwards;} .radius-45 { opacity: 0; animation: showRadius45 0.3s ease-out forwards; animation-delay: 2s; } .radius-30{ opacity: 0; animation: showRadius30 0.3s ease-out forwards; animation-delay: 2s; } .vertical45 { opacity: 0; animation: showVertical45 0.3s ease-out forwards; animation-delay: 2.5s; } .atlasTextRadius { opacity: 0; animation: atlasTextRadiusMov 0.3s ease-out forwards; animation-delay: 2.8s; }</style><style>@keyframes drawCircle { to {stroke-dashoffset: 0; } } @keyframes rotateRadius { from { transform: rotate(0deg); } to   { transform: rotate(-360deg); } } @keyframes showRadius30 { from { opacity: 0; } to { opacity: 1; } } @keyframes showRadius45 { from { opacity: 0; } to { opacity: 1; } }  @keyframes showVertical45 { from { opacity: 0; } to { opacity: 1; } }  @keyframes atlasTextRadiusMov { from { opacity: 0; } to { opacity: 1; } }</style><div class=\"atlasCircleContainer\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 600 300\" class=\"circle-draw\" id=\"svgcirctri0\"> <circle cx=\"300\" cy=\"150\" r=\"148\" transform=\"scale(-1 1) translate(-600 0)  rotate(180 300 150)\"></circle>  <line class=\"radius-line\" x1=\"300\" y1=\"148\" x2=\"448\" y2=\"148\"></line>  <line class=\"vertical45\" x1=\"154\" y1=\"148\" x2=\"300\" y2=\"148\"></line> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"300\" y=\"168\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">d</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"407\" y=\"45\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">C</text> </svg></div></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Graph 1</b>: Circle with circumference C and diameter d.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mn>π</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac><mrow> <mn>C</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>d</mn><mrow> </mfrac></center></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Formula 1</b>: Definition of the constant π, with the values shown in Graph 1.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "The result of **Formula 1** for any circle is given by **Calculation 1** (<htcite0>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "a56b7c6c-93ce-4e7f-bf5e-781e4597485d",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mn>π</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac><mrow> <mn>C</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>d</mn><mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mn>3.141592653589793238462643383279502884197…</mn></center></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 1</b>: Calculation of the value of π.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Note that, despite the large number of digits after the decimal point, which we call decimals, there are still more numbers represented by “…” at the end of the number.\n\nIn this scenario, it is tempting to do as we do with texts and abbreviate, as we saw in the case of kilogram and kilo. However, since pi (π) is a constant well-defined by (π) **Formula 1**, when we cut digits after the decimal point, we are going beyond simply simplifying or rounding: we are ceasing to speak of pi (π).\n\nGiven this explanation, always remember that, if you ever use pi (π) as “3.14,” you will actually no longer be working with pi (π), but with the number “3.14” as if it were π.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_conclusion",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Conclusion\n\nIn this text, we saw that between two numbers we use in counting, such as 0 and 1, there are also numbers that tend to infinity (<htcite0>).\n\nFurthermore, we saw that, although in daily life we make abbreviations, there are scenarios where, by doing so, we completely change the meaning of something, as in the case of the constant pi (π).\n\nFinally, we learned that the numbers after the decimal point are called decimal numbers, a fact that leads us to one final reflection:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "18a901e4-3da3-45d8-a239-fb551e78698e",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Natural Limits",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 5: More Names</b><br /><br />How can we express the relationship between the numbers we count and the numbers that lie between them?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "The answer to this reflection will be presented in the next text.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      }
   ],
   "exercise_v2": [
      {
         "question": "Is any construction—human or natural—that begins with a large base and ends at a point at the top a pyramid?",
         "yesNoAnswer": "No",
         "additionalInfo": "For a construction to be a pyramid, its sides must necessarily be triangular and meet at a point at the top."
      },
      {
         "question": "Does pi (π) have a value different from “3” or “3.1415”?",
         "yesNoAnswer": "Yes",
         "additionalInfo": "The value of pi (π) is the ratio of the circumference to the diameter, with all its infinite decimal digits. Any abbreviated value causes pi (π) to cease being pi (π)."
      }
   ],
   "game_v2": null,
   "date_time": null
}
